Function to clean our input¶

In [ ]:
# Define a function to clean the text data
def clean_text(text, type):
    # Convert to lowercase
    text = text.lower()

    # Remove URLs, mentions, hashtags and newline characters
    text = re.sub(r'http\S+|www.\S+|@\S+|\n', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'#\w+', '', text)
    
    if type == "tweet" :
        # Use TweetTokenizer to tokenize
        tweet_tokenizer = nltk.tokenize.TweetTokenizer()
        tokens = tweet_tokenizer.tokenize(text)
    else:
        tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)

    # Remove numbers
    #tokens = [token for token in tokens if not token.isnumeric()]

    # Remove punctuation
    tokens = [token for token in tokens if token not in  set(string.punctuation)]

    # Remove all unnecessary characters if any
    tokens = [re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9 @ . , : - _]', '', token) for token in tokens]

    # Remove stop words and lemmatize the words
    stop_words = set(nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english'))   
    
    wnl = nltk.WordNetLemmatizer()
    tokens=[wnl.lemmatize(token) for token in tokens if not token in stop_words]
    
    # Remove single-character tokens (mostly punctuation)
    tokens = [token for token in tokens if len(token) > 1]
    
    
    return tokens

In [ ]:
# supporting function
def compute_coherence_values(corpus, dictionary, data, k, alpha='asymmetric', beta='auto'):
    #Using multicore LDA
    ldamodel = LdaMulticore(corpus=corpus,
                       id2word=dictionary,
                       eta=beta,
                       alpha=alpha,
                       num_topics=k,
                       iterations=100,
                       passes=20,
                       random_state=100,
                       eval_every=None,
                       workers = num_processors-1,
                       per_word_topics=True)
    
    coherence_model_lda = CoherenceModel(model=ldamodel, texts=data, dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
    
    return ldamodel, coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()

It is evident that we are able to see better distinct topics as N increased. However with just a coherence score of 0.44 we can also see an overlap in the obtained topics. In order to find the best N, we can perform Hyper parameter tuning.

Tune LDA model¶

To find the optimal number of topics (N) for LDA, you can use the coherence score method. The coherence score measures the degree of semantic similarity between high-scoring words in a topic. The coherence score is calculated based on the top words of each topic, so higher coherence scores indicate better-defined topics.

We will be tuning alpha, beta and number of topics as follows :

In [ ]:
%%time
# Define the range of values for the number of topics to try
min_topics = 2
max_topics = 12
step_size = 1
topics_range = range(min_topics, max_topics+1, step_size)

# Alpha parameter
#alpha = ['asymmetric'] # Run for number of topics only
alpha = list(np.arange(0.01, 1, 0.3))
alpha.append('symmetric')
alpha.append('asymmetric')

# Beta parameter
#beta = ['auto'] # Run for number of topics only
beta = list(np.arange(0.01, 1, 0.3))
beta.append('symmetric')

itr = 0
itr_total = len(beta)*len(alpha)*len(topics_range)
print(f'LDA will execute {itr_total} iterations')

# Create lists to store the coherence scores and the corresponding models
coherence_scores = []
models = []
model_results = {
                 'Topics': [],
                 'Alpha': [],
                 'Beta': [],
                 'Coherence': []
                }


# Iterate over the number of topics to try
for num_topics in topics_range:
    for a in alpha:
        for b in beta:
            itr += 1

            tune_ldamodel, tune_coherence = compute_coherence_values(corpus=tweets_doc_term_matrix,
                           dictionary=tweets_dict,data=tweets_cleaned,k=num_topics,alpha=a,beta=b)


            # Store the coherence score and the corresponding model
            coherence_scores.append(tune_coherence)
            models.append(tune_ldamodel)

            # Save the model results
            model_results['Topics'].append(num_topics)
            model_results['Alpha'].append(a)
            model_results['Beta'].append(b)
            model_results['Coherence'].append(tune_coherence)
            pct_completed = round((itr / itr_total * 100),1)
    print(f'Completed model based on {num_topics} LDA topics. Finished {pct_completed}% of LDA runs')
      

lda_tuning = pd.DataFrame(model_results)
# create a file in your Google Drive
lda_tuning.to_csv('/content/gdrive/My Drive/model/lda_tweets_tuning.csv', index=False)

# Find the model with the highest coherence score
best_model_index = np.argmax(coherence_scores)
best_model = models[best_model_index]
# save the model
best_model.save('/content/gdrive/My Drive/model/lda_tweet_best_model.ldamodel')

The identified topics in tweets in tandem with Microsoft using N=6 are

  • Topic 1 : Video games and gaming (Games, Sony, Xbox, Activision)
  • Topic 2 : Tech companies and products (Apple, Grammarly, Netflix, Canva, Spotify, and Quillbot)
  • Topic 3 : Microsoft Products (Microsoft, 365, Excel)
  • Topic 4 : Business and Media (Facebook, Twitter, Google, Owns, Richest, Guy, Forbes, Bloomberg, Washington Post)
  • Topic 5 : CEO related tweets
  • Topic 6 : Very low weights assigned to its keywords, indicating that it may not be a significant or well-defined topic in the corpus. The keywords in this topic also appear to be somewhat unrelated and do not form a clear topic. It is possible that this topic was generated due to noise or other factors in the data.

As we can see from the printed topics and the pyLDAvis, topics 1, 2, 4 and 5 talk about stocks and market shares. Since there is a high overlap of topics and in order to reduce duplicity we can hyper parameter tune in order to find an ideal N

Tune LDA model¶

In [45]:
%%time
# Define the range of values for the number of topics to try
min_topics = 4
max_topics = 12
step_size = 1
topics_range = range(min_topics, max_topics+1, step_size)


itr = 0
itr_total = len(topics_range)
print(f'LDA will execute {len(topics_range)} iterations')

# Create lists to store the coherence scores and the corresponding models
coherence_scores = []
models = []
model_results = {
                 'Topics': [],
                 'Coherence': []
                }


# Iterate over the number of topics to try
for num_topics in topics_range:
    itr += 1

    #tune_ldamodel, tune_coherence = compute_coherence_values(corpus=news_doc_term_matrix,dictionary=news_dict,data=news_cleaned,k=num_topics)
    tune_ldamodel = LdaMulticore(corpus=news_doc_term_matrix,
                       id2word=news_dict,
                       num_topics=num_topics,
                       passes=20,
                       random_state=100,
                       eval_every=None,
                       workers = num_processors-1,
                       per_word_topics=True)

    coherence_model_lda = CoherenceModel(model=tune_ldamodel, texts=news_cleaned, dictionary=news_dict, coherence='c_v')
    tune_coherence = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence() 

    # Store the coherence score and the corresponding model
    coherence_scores.append(tune_coherence)
    models.append(tune_ldamodel)

    # Save the model results
    model_results['Topics'].append(num_topics)
    model_results['Coherence'].append(tune_coherence)
    pct_completed = round((itr / itr_total * 100),1)
    print(f'Completed model based on {num_topics} LDA topics. Finished {pct_completed}% of LDA runs')

# Plot the coherence scores as a function of the number of topics
plt.plot(topics_range, coherence_scores)
plt.xlabel('Number of Topics')
plt.ylabel('Coherence Score')
plt.show()


lda_tuning = pd.DataFrame(model_results)
# create a file in your Google Drive
lda_tuning.to_csv('/content/gdrive/My Drive/model/lda_news_tuning.csv', index=False)

# Find the model with the highest coherence score
best_model_index = np.argmax(coherence_scores)
best_model = models[best_model_index]
# save the model
best_model.save('/content/gdrive/My Drive/model/lda_news_best_model.ldamodel')

We can observe good distinct topics from the viz. By taking a deeper look into the terms in each topic we can identify the topis as follows

  • Topic 1: Entertainment news (videos, music, etc.)
  • Topic 2: Financial and business news (stocks, markets, etc.)
  • Topic 3: Formatting and styling
  • Topic 4: International news, potentially in a Spanish-speaking country or region
  • Topic 5: Technology and Company news (stocks, prices, etc.)
  • Topic 6: General news (markets, services, business, etc.)
  • Topic 7: Online tracking and privacy, esp. the use of cookies on websites. (cookie, used, set, user, and data)
